I had to actually go inside and ask for a server like he forgot he had a table after 20-30 minutes. He then added items to our check we never ordered and we asked for a manager to speak to after speaking to someone who looked like a manager. Whoever we spoke to then sent the server back out. Big drop in quality and service in the last couple of weeks.  I used to have lunch here at least once a week, often their Ensalada Azteca -- romaine with lots of black olives, heart of palm, slices of red onion, slices of avocado, and added chicken (breast meat, chunked up, slightly crusty and still warm from cooking), delicious dressing.  This time it was all romaine, and VERY scanty representatives of everything else.  Chicken barely cooked and cold.  Instead of the usual dressing serving, this time it came in a tiny cup barely bigger than a thimble.  I said there used to be more chicken (and everything else) with the salad, and a server brought me a little tray of chopped chicken, also undercooked and cold.  I told a different server that this was all much different from how it used to be, and his reply was "We're all new here, so we don't know how it used to be," and apparently didn't care either.   I left most of the salad uneaten, but they still charged me (after my requests) the full $18.63.  I went somewhere else for a real lunch, where you get what you pay for. Los Cuates is steps above your typical burritos-in-a-box generic-menu Mexican place while still feeling cozy, unpretentious, and homey. The chile relleno was absolutely amazing. The dish proudly proclaims it's superiority as it comes out as a barrel-chested magnum-sized pepper with a clearly crisped batter. This is not a limp, sad pepper like so many others. The cheese inside is of high quality. The light painting of mole sauce takes the relleno to another level of distinction. My wife had the chicken stone bowl: the chicken breast was beautifully flavorful, the cheese toothsome and satisfying, and the jalapeno was exceptionally hot (be careful). The only mixed bag at this place are the chips and salsa. The chips are effervescent in how thin and crinkly crispy they are while the salsa is very chunky and difficult to scoop with such a delicate, papery chip.
